And now for more on the special
counsel's investigation into
the president for possible

09:40.000 --> 09:42.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
obstruction of justice, we
are joined by Carrie Johnson.

09:42.966 --> 09:46.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She's the justice
correspondent for NPR.

09:46.066 --> 09:47.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Carrie, welcome
back to the program.

09:47.300 --> 09:49.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
CARRIE JOHNSON, NPR:
Happy to be here.

09:49.366 --> 09:52.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: First of
all, define for us, what
is obstruction of justice?

09:52.100 --> 09:56.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CARRIE JOHNSON: There's
a bunch of obstruction
of justice statutes on
the books, Judy, but,

09:56.200 --> 10:01.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in plain language, it
means trying to interfere
with or impede an official
proceeding, something

10:01.000 --> 10:05.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
like a grand jury investigation,
a congressional investigation.

10:05.100 --> 10:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And prosecutors would have
to prove some kind of bad
intent by the person involved.

10:09.433 --> 10:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And so tell us
what you have been able to learn
about how the special counsel

10:15.600 --> 10:17.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is looking into this.

10:17.700 --> 10:20.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
