kind of politics, there's
an economic story there.

40:16.633 --> 40:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What the elites most
feared was that struggling
whites and people of
color would come together

40:23.733 --> 40:28.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in politics to demand
more of economic elites.

40:28.233 --> 40:31.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, along
the way, as you point out
throughout the book, there were

40:31.633 --> 40:36.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also forces at work to bring
the two -- not just the two,
but to bring all races together.

40:38.700 --> 40:43.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SHERYLL CASHIN: America
has been in this dance
from the beginning.

40:43.000 --> 40:48.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There have been two ideas,
the beautiful, egalitarian,
fundamental idea of universal

40:51.466 --> 40:56.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
human dignity in Thomas
Jefferson's words in
the Declaration of
Independence, but also

40:58.366 --> 41:03.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this regime of white supremacy
that is really designed
to help with capitalism.

41:05.966 --> 41:10.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And throughout this period,
there have always been a small
cadre of people that crossed

41:13.900 --> 41:16.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
lines for alliance or for love.

41:16.333 --> 41:18.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I feature some
of those people.

41:18.433 --> 41:22.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Some of my favorites are
Frederick Douglass and
Thaddeus Stevens, who
not only were radical

41:24.900 --> 41:28.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in their politics, but were
radical enough to have women
of a different race as their

41:29.833 --> 41:31.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
lovers or common law
wives or -- or wives.

41:31.633 --> 41:35.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why were
they able to prevail
in some instances?

41:35.800 --> 41:40.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SHERYLL CASHIN: The
radical Republicans behind
Reconstruction prevailed
with the idea that

41:42.900 --> 41:47.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people of color and progressive
open-minded whites would
come together in politics for

41:49.333 --> 41:52.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the common good and create
things like public education.

41:52.233 --> 41:57.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My bottom line point is that the
class of what I call culturally
dexterous person that's

41:59.233 --> 42:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
open to difference in
this country and wants to
make it work is growing.

42:02.166 --> 42:05.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And that's what
I wanted to ask you, because
you do use the term cultural

42:05.400 --> 42:06.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
dexterity throughout.

42:06.400 --> 42:07.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SHERYLL CASHIN: Right.

42:07.666 --> 42:09.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What
do you mean by that?

42:09.800 --> 42:13.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SHERYLL CASHIN: So, cultural
dexterity is the ability to
enter a situation where you

42:15.633 --> 42:20.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are outnumbered by a
different group and
experience that with comfort,
even wonder, an enhanced

42:24.100 --> 42:27.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
capacity for dealing with
people of a different group.

42:27.100 --> 42:29.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It's the opposite
of colorblindness.

42:29.666 --> 42:34.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the ability to see
and understand difference
and accept it, rather
than sort of demanding

42:36.800 --> 42:40.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that someone else assimilate
to your cultural norms.

42:40.033 --> 42:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why do
you think it's spreading?

42:42.033 --> 42:45.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know there are people who
look at the racial divide in
this country today and say, yes,

42:45.800 --> 42:48.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have made progress, but we
have such a long way to go.

42:48.800 --> 42:50.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
SHERYLL CASHIN:
Yes, I will agree.

42:50.333 --> 42:54.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I acknowledge that we're in
a state of toxic polarity.

42:54.966 --> 42:59.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But all I'm saying is that I
believe we're going to get to
a point where a critical mass

43:01.966 --> 43:05.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of folks, particularly white
people in this country, have
accepted the loss of centrality

43:06.533 --> 43:08.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of whiteness.

43:08.566 --> 43:13.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And when you combine those folks
with growing populations of
people of color, you're going

43:14.933 --> 43:19.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get a majority coalition
that will fight together
for the common good.

43:21.700 --> 43:25.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Even if, along
the way, you may always have
a group of people who fiercely

43:26.500 --> 43:27.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
believe something different.

43:27.766 --> 43:29.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SHERYLL CASHIN: Yes.

43:29.866 --> 43:33.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm not saying that interracial
relationships are going to make
racism go away, or -- nothing

43:33.133 --> 43:34.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like that.

43:34.900 --> 43:39.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There will always
probably be some people,
unfortunately, that are racist.

43:40.266 --> 43:42.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But I think they're
a minority now.

43:42.533 --> 43:47.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think they
will continue to be a
minority in this country.

43:47.466 --> 43:52.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what gives me hope is that
there is a growing population
of folks who like diversity

43:54.633 --> 43:59.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and want to make it work and
want to be part of the coalition
for bringing everybody along.

44:01.833 --> 44:06.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sheryll Cashin,
the book is "Loving: Interracial
Intimacy in America and

44:06.266 --> 44:08.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Threat to White Supremacy,"

44:08.833 --> 44:11.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Thank you very much.

44:11.500 --> 44:16.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
SHERYLL CASHIN:
Thank you so much.

44:19.033 --> 44:24.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: When the death
camps and ghettos of Europe were
liberated at the end of World

44:26.400 --> 44:30.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
War II, a psychologist
from Chicago visited former
prisoners and recorded
dozens of interviews.

44:32.300 --> 44:37.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David Boder's recordings are
among the earliest testimonies
from Holocaust survivors.

44:37.033 --> 44:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And long-missing reels of
songs from this collection
were recently discovered at the

44:41.433 --> 44:44.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
University of Akron, Ohio.

44:44.133 --> 44:48.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From PBS station WVIZ
ideastream in Cleveland,
David C. Barnett reports.

44:48.266 --> 44:53.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: Jon Endres
gingerly threads a thin silver
strand of wire through a machine

44:55.733 --> 44:59.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that will reproduce some
sounds unheard for decades.

44:59.633 --> 45:04.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON ENDRES, University of Akron:
It runs much like a reel-to-reel
tape player, if you remember

45:07.566 --> 45:09.300 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
those.

45:09.300 --> 45:11.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DAVID C. BARNETT: Endres
is a media specialist at
the University of Akron.

45:11.900 --> 45:16.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His colleague James Newhall
spent three years building this
playback machine from spare

45:16.766 --> 45:20.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
parts scrounged from
electronic stores and eBay.

45:20.333 --> 45:25.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The goal was to play some
mysterious recordings
made by psychologist
David Boder over 70 years

45:26.433 --> 45:28.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ago on a wire recorder.

45:28.466 --> 45:31.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BAKER, Cummings Center
for the History of Psychology:
One of Boder's areas of interest

45:31.733 --> 45:36.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and an important area of
his work was his work on
the measurement of trauma.

45:38.766 --> 45:43.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That was the basis of his grant
in 1946 to travel to Europe to
interview a group of traumatized

45:47.433 --> 45:48.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
people.

45:48.866 --> 45:52.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And this included many
survivors of the Holocaust.

45:52.933 --> 45:56.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A collection of Boder material
was deposited here in 1967.

45:56.900 --> 46:01.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it included some
instruments and apparatus,
documents, and it included
a box of wire recordings.

46:03.666 --> 46:07.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MAN: One, two, three,
one two, three.

46:07.066 --> 46:10.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID BAKER: Scholars
were telling us that
there was a missing reel.

46:10.800 --> 46:15.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There was a reel of songs
that were sung to Boder by
Holocaust survivors in a camp in

46:17.533 --> 46:19.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
France after the war.

46:19.633 --> 46:23.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We had a box of reels, and
scholars would ask from time
to time, do you know what's

46:23.000 --> 46:24.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on those?

46:24.333 --> 46:26.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And we had to say, no, we don't.

46:26.366 --> 46:29.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID C. BARNETT:
But now they do.

46:29.033 --> 46:34.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN: We are reproducing on this
spool a set of songs that have
been recorded 50 kilometers

46:39.200 --> 46:42.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of Paris at a colony
of displaced persons.

46:42.433 --> 46:47.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: Baker
says the recent discovery
of this long-missing
reel of songs in the

46:48.900 --> 46:52.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Cummings Center archives has
sparked worldwide interest.

46:52.933 --> 46:57.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DAVID BAKER: Two of the
songs were sung by a
woman named Guta Frank.

47:00.433 --> 47:05.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Guta Frank had survived
a number of the ghettos
in Poland, eventually
ending up in a -- doing

47:12.533 --> 47:17.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
forced labor at a
munitions factory.

47:22.366 --> 47:27.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One song they translated for
us: "Our village is burning."

47:29.266 --> 47:32.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In singing the song, she changed
the lyric from, "Our village
is burning" to "The Jewish

47:37.266 --> 47:39.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
people are burning."

47:39.400 --> 47:44.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In introducing the song, Guta
Frank discussed the fact that
the composer's daughter would

47:46.200 --> 47:50.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sing this song in basements in
the Krakow ghetto, inspiring
people to rebel against

47:53.233 --> 47:55.733 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Nazis.

47:55.733 --> 47:59.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: For
concentration camp prisoners
who had no means of
writing down and preserving

48:04.500 --> 48:09.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what was happening to them,
they could sing songs about
it to each other and pass the

48:09.166 --> 48:11.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
stories down in
an oral tradition.

48:11.900 --> 48:16.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Australian researcher
Joseph Toltz focuses the
music of the Holocaust.

48:16.200 --> 48:19.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, in this specialized
field, he's heard it all.

48:19.333 --> 48:24.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSEPH TOLTZ, Researcher:
This was a beloved song
that traveled around the
entire Yiddish-speaking

48:24.300 --> 48:27.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
world, even to America
and other places.

48:27.033 --> 48:31.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: Toltz is
particularly impressed with the
clarity of the Akron recordings.

48:31.133 --> 48:35.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSEPH TOLTZ: This is a
technology that is 60, 70 years
old and completely outdated.

48:35.900 --> 48:40.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And they have done it
in such a way that has
brought a completely
new quality to the sound

48:42.333 --> 48:44.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that is sort of trapped
in these wire recordings.

48:44.666 --> 48:48.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: Jon
Endres was the one who
made the digital transfer.

48:48.133 --> 48:50.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JON ENDRES: I remember
hearing Krakow.

48:50.766 --> 48:55.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I remember recognizing
some of the more German words
in Yiddish, and knowing full

48:57.766 --> 49:02.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
well they were saying things
along the lines of burning and
dying, and it was extremely

49:03.100 --> 49:04.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
intense.

49:04.600 --> 49:08.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BAKER: It's a bit like
hearing the voice of a ghost.

49:10.400 --> 49:13.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Here are voices that have
been silent for 70 years.

49:13.500 --> 49:18.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And, all of a sudden,
they're singing.

49:19.366 --> 49:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they're singing to us.

49:22.266 --> 49:27.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID C. BARNETT: For the
"PBS NewsHour," I'm David
C. Barnett in Akron, Ohio.

49:36.533 --> 49:41.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to another
in our Brief But Spectacular
series, where we ask people

49:48.833 --> 49:50.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to describe their passions.

49:50.800 --> 49:55.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tonight, we hear from legendary
talk show host Dick Cavett,
whose in-depth discussions

49:55.533 --> 50:00.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
kept American television
audiences entertained and
intellectually engaged
for more than five

50:01.066 --> 50:03.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
decades.

50:03.100 --> 50:07.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
His latest book is "Brief
Encounters: Conversations, Magic
Moments, and Assorted Hijinks."

50:09.533 --> 50:11.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DICK CAVETT, Author, "Brief
Encounters: Conversations,
Magic Moments, and
Assorted Hijinks": Somebody

50:11.600 --> 50:14.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said once, what's the secret
of doing a successful, what's
the Brits call a chat show?

50:15.933 --> 50:20.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
If there is a secret,
it was enunciated by
the great Jack Paar.

50:20.200 --> 50:21.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He said, "Kid, don't
do interviews."

50:21.800 --> 50:25.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I said, "Well, what do
I do Jack, read to them?"

50:25.133 --> 50:30.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He said, "Make it
a conversation."

50:33.666 --> 50:38.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
People ask me, what kind of
show did you decide to do or how
would you describe your show?

50:40.700 --> 50:44.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I have never been able
to come up with an answer for
that, because of the fact that

50:45.200 --> 50:47.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I never had any plan.

50:47.233 --> 50:51.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All I knew was I was being
thrown into and responsible for
90 minutes of live television.

50:53.233 --> 50:58.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I had the advantage of
having seen great examples of
what I would be doing by Jack

50:59.633 --> 51:03.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Paar, Merv Griffin, Johnny
Carson, all of whom I wrote for.

51:03.166 --> 51:06.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHNNY CARSON, "The Tonight
Show": Would you welcome,
please, Mr. Dick Cavett?

51:06.200 --> 51:08.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

51:08.300 --> 51:12.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DICK CAVETT: With Johnny, of
course, you could turn him on
in your head, how he will word

51:15.100 --> 51:17.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it, how many
syllables he will use.

51:17.166 --> 51:21.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
All of that comes together to
make you able to write a line
that they can come out and

51:21.600 --> 51:23.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
say and sound like themselves.

51:23.000 --> 51:26.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Will you welcome, please,
Mr. Marlon Brando?

51:26.066 --> 51:27.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

51:27.766 --> 51:30.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DICK CAVETT: I was just
slap-happy delirious to
have Marlon Brando on

51:30.733 --> 51:35.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And my director admitted later
that he said, when Brando
threw that million-dollar grin

51:36.933 --> 51:40.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in a close-up shot,
I couldn't cut away.

51:40.433 --> 51:44.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My wife's favorite line from
that show is when I said:

51:44.366 --> 51:47.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Were you happy with the way
"The Godfather" came out?

51:47.100 --> 51:50.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARLON BRANDO, Actor: I would
rather not talk about movies.

51:50.033 --> 51:51.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't think they're...

51:51.200 --> 51:53.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

51:53.233 --> 51:57.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DICK CAVETT: I had the luck
of meeting and sitting with
Katharine Hepburn, Bette Davis,

51:59.100 --> 52:03.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Orson Welles, Fred Astaire,
Groucho Marx, Alfred Hitchcock,
Robert Mitchum, oh, and

52:05.633 --> 52:07.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the great John Huston.

52:07.833 --> 52:12.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Somebody semi-humorously warned
me, "You're becoming the poster
boy for depression," because

52:14.833 --> 52:18.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would -- chose to talk about
it, because I found that,
